<font color="#FF0000">ANGER, SIN &amp; HOPE FOR TOMORROW</font><br>
<tt>Tue Aug 19 11:31:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Ed, MUSTANG TWO FOUR, Humming Bird, <br>
For the first time in 30 years I have begun to have dreams of those I served with in Nam. I don't know if it is because of the book or the themes, thoughts and what others like you have shared here.<br>
They are not bad dreams, not nightmares. Did we dream in Nam?<br>
They are but images of individuals I have and have not contacted. Last night I dreamed of the Company represented by a computer being smashed to bits by others for no purpose other then their own amusement and to hide their jealously. <br>
Ed in this thread have put into words what my mind had not yet considered, what I had refused to consider what I have struggled with. <br>
The local papers have called me all sorts of things, but in the little print the public often applause where I stand and appreciate what I say. I anger many, not for what I say, often the Press and the public appreciate what I say, but it is the way I say it that bothers them. Guess I should show more deplomacy while I cut their throats.I mean I should at least use a clean knife, so that they won't come down with some infection, I should be more sensitive to the feelings of others.  <br>
But is there not also righteous anger dwelling, residing in our hearts? Is that wrong?<br>
Does not the injustice we see in this world cause us much pain?  <br>
Are we the corrupt individuals because we do not share the same views of others? Where and when are we suppose to embrace everyone as brothers yet still maintain our standards? Who says we are supposed to do that?<br>
 <br>
One day I had turned in a police, impound report to my Sgt. at the police department. Unknown to him the department had changed the process whereas we no longer needed a supervisor's signature on some reports. When he read my unsigned police report he became unclued. Became quite angry with me, although I was in the right. <br>
Still he wrote me up. When I challenged his authority and his report of the incident and requested my captain's intervention. He had to withdraw his false accusation against me, but in the process, I had made an enemy. <br>
Later that same afternoon while I was taking a drink from a water fountain he came up behind me and said,<br>
&quot;Barela, I'm going to get you, sooner or later I'm going to get you.&quot;<br>
In that moment now 15-17 years pass, I had my first Vietnam flashback. I saw the fields of battle, the destruction reeked upon us and what we reeked upon the enemy, I saw those I had served with, as we stood united in battle.<br>
I realized there and then that, that police Sgt. did not understand the value of life. He had no idea of what life was really all about. His corporate world was his life.<br>
I believe that much of my anger resides because I have not found peace with a job we left unaccomplished. Because when I left the battlefield the fighting was still going on, because as our newsletter says, <br>
&quot;I don't know what happened, but when I left we were winning!&quot;<br>
Ed, you and I, and I believe I can say this from what I have read in your posts, do not like to leave things undone. We want to improve things, make things right but we face a world that is hostile to our thinking because its so much easier to leave things as they are. <br>
Why rock the boat and when we do we shame others for their lack of commitment and unwillingness to walk point or even support us when we do. <br>
We're caretakers and feel a responsibility for those we still see pinned down behind rice paddy dikes and under wooden bridges. <br>
After the Ronnie King riots I could no longer work as an officer, the department began to render only lip and drive-by service. 250 other officers and I left the department within a few short months after that. It was no longer the department we had joined. That angered me, but I knew there was nothing I could do.<br>
What has helped? <br>
My family, friends, solitude, examining often my motives for what I do and how I do it. Listening to others, sharing what I can from what my life's journey has though me, acknowledging that God's hand has been upon me for a purpose. Finding that purpose daily and at night thanking Him for what I was able to do. Where I failed I ask for forgiveness and try to do better the following day and in the morning, before I sit to work on the book, I now read these threads and reflect, enjoy,  laugh, think about what has been said. Sorry, if I have ever removed the JESUS NUT off your chopper!-<br>
Often I wonder if I laid a rat trap or if a rat trap's been laid for me, but I shrug if off and realize that life is full of bobby traps and at times I find myself touching the past with what is written here and that helps me with my writing and if I feel a need, I know that here I can fire off a volley or a full belt of tracers for effect, get some feedback and appreciate you and others and when Spatz writes I realize how fortunate I am and go on with life. <br><br>

